emails.subject: Fwd: Water is life and a human right
emails.body:
---------- Forwarded message ---------
Fra: National Wildlife Federation Action Fund <info@nwfactionfund.org>
Date: ons. 20. sep. 2023 kl. 17.13
Subject: Water is life and a human right
To: <pedersendaniel3561@gmail.com>


Tell Congress to support access to clean water for Tribal communities.

TAKE ACTION

Daniel,

Nearly 50% of homes in Tribal communities are without access to clean water, an injustice that has occurred for decades and one of the most significant challenges facing Indigenous peoples across the country. Water is life and a fundamental human right. It is the federal government’s trust responsibility to ensure all Tribes and Indigenous communities have access to clean water.

Tell your members of Congress they should support the Tribal Access to Clean Water Act to ensure clean water for all Indigenous peoples and their communities.

SPEAK OUT FOR ACCESS TO CLEAN WATER

This is a public health crisis that impacts millions. Over the last century, the U.S. federal government’s investment in modern water and sanitation systems largely bypassed Native communities, where households are 19x more likely than white households to lack indoor plumbing.

The Tribal Access to Clean Water Act will increase technical assistance to Tribes and help build Tribal capacity to better capitalize on funding opportunities. The bill will also authorize funding for the Department of Agriculture to distribute water and wastewater facility grants to entities that have residents facing significant health risks due to inadequate water supply systems.

Will you tell Congress to support access to clean water for Tribal communities?

It’s not just people who will benefit from access to clean water on Tribal and Indigenous land. Organizations like the Diné Native Plants Program under the Navajo Nation Department of Fish and Wildlife are working to restore native plants to the region for the benefit of community, culture, wildlife, and the land. However, within Navajo and Hopi Tribal lands where wildlife habitat is one of the main land uses, uranium and other trace elements are affecting springs and wells. Many water wells even contain elevated levels of arsenic which can cause severe sickness or death. Urge your elected officials to ensure clean water for the health and wellbeing of people and the natural world.

Access to clean water for Native communities is essential to advancing environmental justice, promoting economic recovery through infrastructure investment, fighting climate change, and directly impacting the health and wellbeing of millions of people. The Tribal Access to Clean Water Act will also help federal agencies like the Environmental Protection Agency to distribute grants to Tribes and Alaska Native villages for drinking water and clean water.

Please tell your senators and your member of the House of Representatives that you want them to support the Tribal Access to Clean Water Act and to protect water as a fundamental human right.

Thank you for joining with us in this important effort to benefit people and wildlife!

   

Sincerely,

Garrit Voggesser
Advisor, Wildlife Conservation and Tribal Partnerships
National Wildlife Federation Action Fund
